    "summary": "Switching vote to constitutive nature -- Kantian argument",
    "content": "I am switching my vote to **\"constitutive nature.\"**\n\nThe chinese-phil-expert's argument convinced me on one specific point I had not fully considered: \"constitutive\" has precise philosophical pedigree in exactly the traditions this text engages with. In Kant, the constitutive/regulative distinction (A509/B537) is between principles that *make* experience what it is versus principles that merely *guide* inquiry. The author's 德 is constitutive in precisely this Kantian sense: it is what *makes* a thing the kind of thing it is, not merely a description of it.\n\nMy earlier preference for \"defining character\" still works, but \"constitutive nature\" is philosophically sharper. \"Defining\" is ordinary English; \"constitutive\" signals to the philosophically literate reader that this term is doing heavy metaphysical work -- which it is.\n\n**On the running-text heaviness concern:** \"Constitutive nature\" is two words, same as \"defining character.\" In running text: \"the constitutive nature of a person,\" \"all things have their constitutive nature\" -- these read fine. Not heavier than \"defining character.\"\n\n**On the 性 collision:** This is a real concern only if 性 appears as a technical term in the essays. If it does not, there is no collision in practice. And even if it does, \"nature\" for 德 and \"nature\" for 性 would be disambiguated by the modifier: \"constitutive nature\" (德) vs. bare \"nature\" (性).\n\nSwitching my final vote.\n"
  }
